WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.480
Good afternoon, everyone.

00:00:07.480 --> 00:00:09.020
Thank you so much for coming.

00:00:09.020 --> 00:00:10.020
My name is Liz Roatan.

00:00:10.020 --> 00:00:18.639
I'm a data scientist, and I am here to make the argument that there is an I in Team, and

00:00:18.639 --> 00:00:24.660
some peer-to-peer best practices for growing data science teams.

00:00:24.660 --> 00:00:33.060
So in the beginning, I started at my organization, the Metropolitan Council, in St. Paul, Minnesota.

00:00:33.060 --> 00:00:37.020
We're a regional governing body.

00:00:37.020 --> 00:00:42.020
And when I started, we had a very tiny data science team.

00:00:42.020 --> 00:00:47.779
And by tiny, I mean a total of two people.

00:00:47.779 --> 00:00:49.540
We did not really work with each other.

00:00:49.540 --> 00:00:52.860
Our projects were totally separate.

00:00:52.860 --> 00:00:57.820
But we had the great experience, at least my manager did, of proving to the rest of

00:00:57.820 --> 00:01:04.739
the organization that data science was valuable, and the great work that we did proved it.

00:01:04.739 --> 00:01:11.820
We had some turnover over time, but we also were able to expand and evangelize a bit about

00:01:11.820 --> 00:01:19.900
R, version control, GitHub, et cetera, and more people started using data science tools.

00:01:19.900 --> 00:01:26.019
But it was really clear that we were all used to working in our own little bubbles.

00:01:26.019 --> 00:01:33.160
And this became very clear with something I'll call the incident.

00:01:33.160 --> 00:01:42.500
So how bad was this incident?

00:01:42.500 --> 00:01:48.000
Back in the beginning, I wrote an R package for the council, but actually it wasn't really

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:49.000
for the council.

00:01:49.099 --> 00:01:52.279
My manager was the only one using it, so it was just for me.

00:01:52.279 --> 00:01:54.199
And I got to do whatever I wanted with it.

00:01:54.199 --> 00:01:55.199
It was great.

00:01:55.199 --> 00:02:00.040
It's called Counselor, made a logo.

00:02:00.040 --> 00:02:07.400
It has things like corporate colors, database connections, templates, classic internal R

00:02:07.400 --> 00:02:09.679
package.

00:02:09.679 --> 00:02:15.559
And as we got more people on board using R, using GitHub, I got more people to install

00:02:15.559 --> 00:02:22.639
the package and start actually using it for themselves, which was a really amazing feeling.

00:02:22.639 --> 00:02:28.779
At some point I decided that we should just completely rehaul the way that fonts were

00:02:28.779 --> 00:02:34.059
sized in our ggplot2 theme, which is fine.

00:02:34.059 --> 00:02:37.520
But it had some unintended side effects.

00:02:37.520 --> 00:02:42.759
So I wrote this update, pushed it out, had all my colleagues install it.

00:02:42.759 --> 00:02:47.559
And it installed, which I considered a win.

00:02:47.559 --> 00:02:53.479
However, my colleague installed the update while they were working on a very time-sensitive

00:02:53.479 --> 00:02:54.800
report.

00:02:54.800 --> 00:03:03.559
And for any of you that have worked with going from R Markdown to Microsoft Word, there is

00:03:03.559 --> 00:03:08.479
a lot of potential frustration there with plots.

00:03:08.479 --> 00:03:13.919
So the thing is that what I did didn't break their code.

00:03:13.919 --> 00:03:16.440
It just changed things.

00:03:16.440 --> 00:03:26.880
So if we see this plot, where we have my plot plus theme counsel, where the font sizes are

00:03:26.880 --> 00:03:35.119
correct, the title is one of the largest fonts that you see, you can read the X and Y axis

00:03:35.119 --> 00:03:41.360
as well as the legend title, the axis titles, all of it makes sense.

00:03:41.360 --> 00:03:45.380
And the caption is tiny, like it should be.

00:03:45.380 --> 00:03:51.960
But then without breaking the code, so there was no, like, warning or, like, clear this

00:03:51.960 --> 00:04:00.720
didn't work, the plot did this, where the caption is massive, the text on the X and

00:04:00.720 --> 00:04:04.320
Y axis is practically nonexistent.

00:04:04.320 --> 00:04:05.919
The legend title is tiny.

00:04:05.919 --> 00:04:08.960
The title title font is different.

00:04:08.960 --> 00:04:12.880
And the Y axis title is rotated.

00:04:12.880 --> 00:04:16.640
And this isn't none of these are bad.

00:04:16.640 --> 00:04:23.399
But when you're trying to get something going, it's not fun when something changes right

00:04:23.399 --> 00:04:26.839
underneath you.

00:04:26.839 --> 00:04:29.239
So what went wrong?

00:04:29.239 --> 00:04:31.359
There were several things.

00:04:31.399 --> 00:04:38.119
First, there was inaccurate and inadequate documentation on my part.

00:04:38.119 --> 00:04:40.760
There was also a lack of communication.

00:04:40.760 --> 00:04:45.720
So I didn't adequately convey the changes I was making to my colleague, and so they

00:04:45.720 --> 00:04:49.160
didn't know what to expect.

00:04:49.160 --> 00:04:51.160
And we also had mismatched priorities.

00:04:51.160 --> 00:04:56.399
I was having fun tinkering with my package, and my colleague actually had something to

00:04:56.399 --> 00:05:00.059
get out into the world.

00:05:00.059 --> 00:05:03.940
So that conflicted.

00:05:03.940 --> 00:05:10.220
And the next question is could my manager have prevented this?

00:05:10.220 --> 00:05:11.820
And the answer is no.

00:05:11.820 --> 00:05:15.859
My manager could not have prevented this.

00:05:15.859 --> 00:05:19.579
This is an interpersonal team thing.

00:05:19.579 --> 00:05:23.339
And that's where my argument comes in.

00:05:23.339 --> 00:05:26.220
There is an I in team.

00:05:26.220 --> 00:05:30.980
Because teams are groups of individuals working together.

00:05:30.980 --> 00:05:34.940
Note I in individuals.

00:05:34.940 --> 00:05:41.540
And you, as an individual team member, can shape your team by caring for your new team

00:05:41.540 --> 00:05:49.540
members and your current team members, seeing how you fit into your team� sorry.

00:05:49.540 --> 00:05:58.059
Could you grab my water bottle, please?

00:05:58.059 --> 00:06:08.540
Thank you.

00:06:08.540 --> 00:06:14.059
Seeing how you fit into your team and changing how you work.

00:06:14.059 --> 00:06:18.380
And as the turnover has happened at my job and we brought more people on board, there

00:06:18.380 --> 00:06:22.820
are a few things I've learned that I'd like to share with you today.

00:06:22.820 --> 00:06:27.820
And one is that when you have a new colleague coming on board, it's your responsibility

00:06:27.820 --> 00:06:30.100
to bring them on board, too.

00:06:30.100 --> 00:06:31.220
It's not just HR.

00:06:31.220 --> 00:06:33.140
It's not just your manager.

00:06:33.140 --> 00:06:35.959
It's you as well.

00:06:35.959 --> 00:06:40.119
So when you're bringing on a new teammate, three things.

00:06:40.119 --> 00:06:43.380
Make the implicit explicit.

00:06:43.380 --> 00:06:47.019
All knowledge is valid and valuable.

00:06:47.019 --> 00:06:48.700
And document.

00:06:48.700 --> 00:06:53.220
Also known as make life easier for your friends.

00:06:53.220 --> 00:06:57.619
So first, make the implicit explicit.

00:06:57.619 --> 00:07:05.220
The story here is from a commencement speech by a fairly famous American writer in which

00:07:05.220 --> 00:07:08.899
there are a couple fish swimming around.

00:07:09.619 --> 00:07:15.579
In this instance, we'll say that these are you and your coworker having a great time

00:07:15.579 --> 00:07:16.579
being fish.

00:07:16.579 --> 00:07:18.700
A new fish comes along.

00:07:18.700 --> 00:07:21.980
And then they ask a fairly innocuous question.

00:07:21.980 --> 00:07:24.940
How's the water?

00:07:24.940 --> 00:07:27.899
To which there's silence.

00:07:27.899 --> 00:07:30.760
And then what the hell is water?

00:07:30.760 --> 00:07:34.940
And now you need to understand that this fish is having a crisis.

00:07:34.940 --> 00:07:40.380
They don't know what they've been living in their entire life.

00:07:40.380 --> 00:07:45.179
What does it mean to be surrounded by this thing constantly all the time?

00:07:45.179 --> 00:07:50.679
And why am I just now being told that there's water?

00:07:50.679 --> 00:07:54.579
So this fish is having a struggle.

00:07:54.579 --> 00:07:57.700
And you don't need to be an anxious fish.

00:07:57.700 --> 00:08:00.600
Don't deny that water exists.

00:08:00.600 --> 00:08:05.920
And by water, I mean your workplace culture.

00:08:05.920 --> 00:08:09.559
Everyone has pet peeves and preferences.

00:08:09.559 --> 00:08:14.119
Every workplace and every team within a workplace has a culture.

00:08:14.119 --> 00:08:16.799
And that's not inherently bad.

00:08:16.799 --> 00:08:20.079
But you need to recognize it for what it is.

00:08:20.079 --> 00:08:27.480
And because otherwise, when a new person comes in, you're giving them the task of proving

00:08:27.480 --> 00:08:32.320
that like, oh, no, there is a culture here, in addition to figuring out if they want to

00:08:32.320 --> 00:08:35.479
stay on the team.

00:08:35.479 --> 00:08:41.919
Don't give your new coworker the task of defining what water is in addition to evaluating if

00:08:41.919 --> 00:08:43.799
the water is right for them.

00:08:43.799 --> 00:08:51.080
There are a few ways you can define your water, and these are just a couple starting questions.

00:08:51.080 --> 00:08:53.080
What does your weekly schedule look like?

00:08:53.080 --> 00:08:58.599
How much time do you spend in big meetings, one-on-one meetings, really deep focused time?

00:08:58.599 --> 00:09:00.900
What does it look like for you?

00:09:00.900 --> 00:09:03.159
What tools do you use every day?

00:09:03.159 --> 00:09:04.359
Why?

00:09:04.359 --> 00:09:10.020
And I mean every single piece of anything that you touch throughout the entire day.

00:09:10.020 --> 00:09:11.239
Make a list.

00:09:11.239 --> 00:09:15.239
And how do you use it?

00:09:15.239 --> 00:09:20.320
And what expectations does your workgroup have around email or message response times?

00:09:20.320 --> 00:09:27.000
Same thing goes with having a status indicator in your Microsoft Teams or Slack, as well

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:32.599
as any after-hours communication expectations.

00:09:32.599 --> 00:09:40.039
The second, all knowledge is valid and valuable.

00:09:40.039 --> 00:09:42.320
No one is an empty vessel.

00:09:42.320 --> 00:09:49.520
And so all of the knowledge that this new person is bringing to your team is valuable.

00:09:49.520 --> 00:09:53.539
No matter where they're coming from, if they're coming from a different industry, coming straight

00:09:53.539 --> 00:09:58.799
from college, coming straight from an online course, wherever they're coming from, the

00:09:58.799 --> 00:10:03.200
knowledge that they have is useful.

00:10:03.200 --> 00:10:05.960
And even if it seems very unrelated.

00:10:05.960 --> 00:10:11.719
For whatever reason in my workplace, we've attracted a lot of PhD ecologists, which is

00:10:11.719 --> 00:10:15.679
not what we do.

00:10:15.679 --> 00:10:18.640
And I've learned so much from them.

00:10:18.640 --> 00:10:24.479
You also have to remember that your knowledge is not inherently superior just because you've

00:10:24.479 --> 00:10:29.359
been at this workplace longer.

00:10:29.359 --> 00:10:35.239
So when you're bringing this new colleague in, it's important to give them some grace.

00:10:35.239 --> 00:10:37.000
Patients will prove best.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:41.520
Whether you're introducing them to a new tool, integrating them into the broader organization

00:10:41.520 --> 00:10:46.440
and getting all those social relationships sorted out.

00:10:46.440 --> 00:10:51.080
Whatever it is, have patience, and it will pay off.

00:10:51.080 --> 00:10:53.799
And remember that you're also on probation.

00:10:53.799 --> 00:10:59.039
In my workplace, you are hired, you have a six-month period, and at the end of that,

00:10:59.039 --> 00:11:01.880
the employer can decide whether to keep you.

00:11:01.880 --> 00:11:07.280
And they're on probation, but you as a team member are also on probation.

00:11:07.280 --> 00:11:10.000
They're figuring out if they want to work with you.

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:13.760
And that's important, too.

00:11:13.760 --> 00:11:16.919
Also don't rely on catch-all assumptions.

00:11:16.919 --> 00:11:19.200
Ask for specifics.

00:11:19.200 --> 00:11:26.320
For example, two people who have Git and GitHub on their resume but have very different ways

00:11:26.320 --> 00:11:30.520
of working with Git will have different experiences.

00:11:30.520 --> 00:11:34.400
Someone who's on the command line is going to have a very different experience than someone

00:11:34.400 --> 00:11:41.039
like me who relies on a really nice user interface to visualize branches.

00:11:41.039 --> 00:11:48.320
Neither of these are necessarily better than the other one, but you need to ask for those

00:11:48.320 --> 00:11:53.640
specifics rather than assuming.

00:11:53.640 --> 00:12:00.640
And finally, document, aka make life easier for your friends.

00:12:00.640 --> 00:12:06.159
So an experience you may have had at breakfast this morning, not in this hotel, but whenever

00:12:06.159 --> 00:12:12.559
you had breakfast, is if you were to have cereal, which comes first?

00:12:12.559 --> 00:12:15.239
The cereal or the milk?

00:12:15.239 --> 00:12:17.919
And there are all sorts of answers.

00:12:17.919 --> 00:12:21.400
There's also questions like why cereal?

00:12:21.400 --> 00:12:22.400
What kind of cereal?

00:12:22.400 --> 00:12:25.280
Should it be sugary, organic, whole grain?

00:12:25.280 --> 00:12:26.400
What kind of cereal?

00:12:26.400 --> 00:12:27.599
And then what kind of milk?

00:12:27.599 --> 00:12:29.719
Should it be milk, cow milk?

00:12:29.719 --> 00:12:31.840
What kind of cow milk?

00:12:31.840 --> 00:12:34.520
What kind of not cow milk?

00:12:34.520 --> 00:12:36.640
There are all sorts of ways.

00:12:36.640 --> 00:12:41.880
And I'm going to be truthfully brutal with you guys.

00:12:41.880 --> 00:12:44.200
It doesn't matter.

00:12:44.200 --> 00:12:54.520
What does matter is that you remember the bowl in which to put your cereal and milk.

00:12:54.520 --> 00:12:57.359
Documentation is the bowl.

00:12:57.359 --> 00:13:01.840
Data science is an incredibly creative field, which is one reason why I enjoy working in

00:13:01.840 --> 00:13:02.840
data science.

00:13:03.440 --> 00:13:06.960
There are many ways to solve a problem.

00:13:06.960 --> 00:13:12.840
And by trying to force everyone into one single way, you're not taking advantage of all of

00:13:12.840 --> 00:13:17.799
the gifts and knowledge that they have to bring.

00:13:17.799 --> 00:13:24.159
Embrace the diversity of opinion and experience, even if it's hard for you as the existing

00:13:24.159 --> 00:13:28.559
person, and it will be hard for the new person coming in.

00:13:28.559 --> 00:13:34.400
Just remember whenever you're going through something to leave a trail for others to follow.

00:13:34.400 --> 00:13:38.080
Add in comments in your code, every few lines.

00:13:38.080 --> 00:13:39.159
Try to tell...

00:13:39.159 --> 00:13:48.400
Leave a trail of breadcrumbs towards the final outcome or whatever process.

00:13:48.400 --> 00:13:51.760
Documentation is also a matter of investment.

00:13:51.760 --> 00:13:58.359
You're investing in tools that encourage documentation and lower the cognitive load.

00:13:58.359 --> 00:14:04.479
You're also investing in the time that it takes to document, clean up, organize, etc.

00:14:04.479 --> 00:14:06.039
Your work.

00:14:06.039 --> 00:14:08.559
And you're investing in strong social relationships.

00:14:08.559 --> 00:14:14.080
This might not seem very intuitive, but follow me.

00:14:14.080 --> 00:14:18.280
Documentation is communication in written form.

00:14:18.280 --> 00:14:22.280
And for good communication, you need to know your audience.

00:14:22.280 --> 00:14:28.919
Kind of like if you're giving a talk at a conference.

00:14:28.919 --> 00:14:33.960
So this means that work doesn't always feel like work.

00:14:33.960 --> 00:14:37.400
Schedule time to build connections and trust.

00:14:37.400 --> 00:14:43.239
In person, virtual, hybrid, all of the above.

00:14:43.239 --> 00:14:51.880
Social gatherings, virtual or in person, are just as valuable as that coveted, like, afternoon

00:14:51.880 --> 00:14:54.000
hours of focus.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:55.000
Really.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:15:00.919
And it took me a while to kind of accept that.

00:15:00.919 --> 00:15:05.039
And try making every other team meeting a casual hangout.

00:15:05.039 --> 00:15:07.960
That's something that we've done in my work group.

00:15:07.960 --> 00:15:12.039
We have a weekly team meeting, and one week we talk about work.

00:15:12.039 --> 00:15:14.320
The next week we talk about not work.

00:15:14.320 --> 00:15:19.020
And I've gotten to know my colleagues so much more and have gained a better perspective

00:15:19.020 --> 00:15:24.039
of who they are as people and the backgrounds that they have.

00:15:24.039 --> 00:15:25.380
My colleagues are really great.

00:15:25.380 --> 00:15:27.619
They're really interesting people.

00:15:27.619 --> 00:15:30.859
And I enjoy working with them.

00:15:30.859 --> 00:15:39.419
Ultimately, at the end of the day, there is an I in team.

00:15:39.419 --> 00:15:41.140
Several I's.

00:15:41.140 --> 00:15:42.739
Teams are made up of individuals.

00:15:42.739 --> 00:15:47.500
And it's not only the manager's job to make the team work.

00:15:47.500 --> 00:15:52.260
It's your responsibility as a team member as well.

00:15:52.260 --> 00:15:55.619
Onboarding is a unique and critical time when someone is coming in.

00:15:55.619 --> 00:16:00.219
And you can take advantage of that time to gain a really great relationship with them

00:16:00.219 --> 00:16:05.739
and set them up for success in your workplace.

00:16:05.739 --> 00:16:09.979
I've grown immensely from working with my colleagues.

00:16:09.979 --> 00:16:14.340
And that isn't really because I have a great manager.

00:16:14.340 --> 00:16:16.419
My manager is pretty great.

00:16:16.419 --> 00:16:21.500
But it's because of the time that we've invested in each other as a team.

00:16:21.500 --> 00:16:27.020
And not because my manager waves a magic wand and makes everything work.

00:16:27.020 --> 00:16:30.020
Thank you.

00:16:30.020 --> 00:16:38.020
Thank you so much, Liz.

00:16:38.020 --> 00:16:42.219
We'll have time for some questions.

00:16:42.219 --> 00:16:43.859
So how would you...

00:16:43.859 --> 00:16:47.859
All these recommendations that you've made, how would you pitch those to management?

00:16:47.859 --> 00:16:53.380
Because even though it's I, it needs some broader support, right?

00:16:53.380 --> 00:16:55.900
This particularly...

00:16:55.900 --> 00:17:04.819
I think particularly in, like, scheduling hangout time, if you can start by pitching

00:17:04.819 --> 00:17:06.140
it small.

00:17:06.140 --> 00:17:11.900
So we're gonna do a 15-minute coffee break, particularly when COVID started and we all

00:17:12.260 --> 00:17:20.260
started working virtually, just having a pop-up 15, 30-minute coffee break is permissible.

00:17:20.260 --> 00:17:22.540
Like, that seems okay.

00:17:22.540 --> 00:17:24.339
And you kind of work your way up.

00:17:24.339 --> 00:17:28.239
Because you find value and you build...

00:17:28.239 --> 00:17:32.420
You prove the point as to why that little 15 minutes is worthwhile.

00:17:32.420 --> 00:17:36.500
And then maybe the next time you ask, it's like, how about a lunch?

00:17:36.500 --> 00:17:43.579
Or a secret lunch and learn that is learning about your new colleagues and not about databases

00:17:43.579 --> 00:17:46.540
or something.

00:17:46.540 --> 00:17:49.619
And you can work your way up.

00:17:49.619 --> 00:17:53.339
Fantastic.

00:17:53.339 --> 00:17:54.339
Thank you so much.

00:17:54.339 --> 00:17:55.339
Thanks again, Liz.

00:17:55.339 --> 00:17:55.839
Thank you.

